{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\n`.github/workflows/reconcile-bridge.yml` already has the full key-materialize + job-level\nsigning wiring (story 9e76/cc0b): it reads the `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` secret, masks it\n(`::add-mask::`), writes it to a `0600` file at `${RUNNER_TEMP}/rebar-bot-signing-key`, and\nexports `REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY=<that path>` into `$GITHUB_ENV` (see\n`.github/workflows/reconcile-bridge.yml:217-228`), with the bot email defaulted to\n`joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com` (`:205`, `:267`) so the reconciler-authored events resolve to\nidentity `594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d`. The wiring is **secret-gated**: if `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` is\nempty the materialize step logs \"writes will be unsigned (advisory)\" and exits 0 (`:220-222`),\nso CI writes come out **attributed but unsigned**. This is provisioning + verification of that\nexisting wiring, not new plumbing.\n\n## Precondition — identity + wiring already exist (verified, not created)\n\n- The **Rebar Bot identity** `594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d` already exists (`email\n  joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com`, one registered ed25519 key) — the same identity local signing\n  (79da) uses; CI resolves to it by the `BRIDGE_BOT_EMAIL` default.\n- The **private key** is available from AWS SSM SecureString `/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key`\n  (ADR-0012) — the public half of which is the key registered on 594c.\n- The **GitHub secret `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` is already present** (`gh secret list` shows it,\n  last set 2026-07-14). Because a GitHub secret value cannot be read back, this story\n  **re-sets it from the authoritative SSM source** (to guarantee it is the correct current key)\n  and then **proves** signing by triggering a real run — the secret's mere presence is not\n  proof it holds the right key.\n\n## What\n\nTurn on real CI signing and prove it end-to-end:\n\n- **Re-set** the `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` GitHub Actions secret on `navapbc/rebar` from the SSM\n  private key (`gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar` fed the decrypted SSM\n  value; never echoed).\n- **Trigger** a `reconcile-bridge` run (`workflow_dispatch`; the workflow also runs on a `*/20`\n  cron) and confirm the run's reconciler writes at least one **signed** event authored by\n  identity `594c`, with `rebar verify-identity` reporting it `verified`.\n- If a given run has no inbound Jira delta to translate (so it writes no work-ticket event),\n  re-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event, or use the workflow's own canary\n  write — the AC is satisfied by a real signed event id, not merely a green run.\n\n## Scope\n\nThe GitHub Actions workflows that write tickets (`reconcile-bridge` + its canary). Secret\npopulation + a live signing proof only. No enforcement flip here (8d39); no change to the\nworkflow YAML (the wiring already exists — this story does not modify\n`.github/workflows/reconcile-bridge.yml`). Empty `file_impact` is correct: no tracked repo file\nchanges.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] **Secret populated from SSM.** `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` on `navapbc/rebar` holds the Rebar\n      Bot private key whose public half is registered on identity `594c`. Proving evidence\n      recorded on this ticket: the `gh secret set` outcome + `gh secret list` line showing the\n      updated timestamp. (Value is write-only, so proof is the successful set + the downstream\n      signed event, not a read-back.)\n- [ ] **A CI run produces a signed, verified bot event.** Capture the tickets-branch HEAD\n      before the run: `C=$(git -C .tickets-tracker rev-parse HEAD)`. Trigger a `reconcile-bridge`\n      run; after its ticket writes land (fetch the tickets branch), confirm **both**: (a) the run\n      introduced ≥1 in-scope event authored by `594c` after `C` — evidenced by a new event on a\n      work ticket whose `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` increased, recorded as the\n      ticket id + tickets commit (proves the check is non-vacuous); and (b) every event the run\n      introduced verifies under enforcement:\n      `rebar verify-identity --all --require-authenticated --since \"$C\"` exits 0 (had the bot\n      event been unsigned it would exit non-zero — this is exactly the enforcement the flip will\n      apply). Record `C`, the run URL, and the resulting ticket id on this ticket.\n- [ ] [operator-attested] The secret is set in GitHub settings and a real run proves signing.\n      Evidence recorded on this ticket as a comment: the workflow-run URL, the `gh secret list`\n      timestamp, and the resulting signed event id (+ its `verified` verdict from the command\n      above)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784238781109295001,"uuid":"18746555-59de-430f-b13c-c4406dad1649"}